Data Containers and Data Visualization

Niels Richard Hansen

This vignette demonstrates how to use the classes ContinuousProcess, MarkedPointProcess and JumpProcess as data containers and how to visualize the data they contain.

First we load the example data. The data sets are contExam of class ContinuousProcess, pointExam of class MarkedPointProcess and jumpExam of class JumpProcess.

library(ppstat)
## Loading required package: ggplot2
data(example)

Showing data structure.

contExam
## Class: ContinuousProcess 
## Dimensions: 4004 x 3 
## Index variable: time 
## 
## 4 units.
##    id: A B C D
## 
## 3 variables.
##    gender foo bar

Summarizing the data.

summary(contExam)
## Class: ContinuousProcess 
## Dimensions: 4004 x 3 
## Index variable: time 
## 
## 4 units.
##    id: A B C D
## 
## 3 variables.
##    gender foo bar
## 
##   grid-points time-range gender median(foo) median(bar)
## A        1001     [0;10]      M  -7.4004049    46.72515
## B        1001     [0;10]      M   0.9732583    38.52012
## C        1001     [0;10]      M  18.1055244    14.29927
## D        1001     [0;10]      F   5.0987016    58.12943

Plotting data.

plot(contExam)

Subsetting data.

subset(contExam, id %in% c("C","D","F"))
## Class: ContinuousProcess 
## Dimensions: 2002 x 3 
## Index variable: time 
## 
## 2 units.
##    id: C D
## 
## 3 variables.
##    gender foo bar
subset(contExam, foo > 0)
## Class: ContinuousProcess 
## Dimensions: 2611 x 3 
## Index variable: time 
## 
## 4 units.
##    id: A B C D
## 
## 3 variables.
##    gender foo bar
subset(contExam, gender == "F")
## Class: ContinuousProcess 
## Dimensions: 1001 x 3 
## Index variable: time 
## 
## 3 variables.
##    gender foo bar

Plotting a subset.

plot(subset(contExam, subset = (time > 4 & gender == "F"), select = foo))

Modifying plot using ggplot2.

plot(subset(contExam, id == "A")) + geom_point()

plot(contExam) + facet_null()

More sophisticated plots can be produced, e.g.different uses of faceting and grouping.

plot(contExam) + facet_grid(variable ~ ., scale = "free_y")

To do this depending on unit-specific variables we must specify an additional argument to the plot such that these variables are included in the plot data.

plot(contExam, allUnitData = TRUE) +
  facet_grid(variable ~ gender, scale = "free_y")

Subsetting to non-contiguous subsets of the time axis is possible, but plot assumes a contiguous x-axis and interpolates the graph.

plot(subset(contExam, id == "A" & (time < 2 | time > 4)))

Factor columns are plotting using a different aesthetic mapping.

plot(factExam)
## Warning in plot(plotData, ...): NAs introduced by coercion
## Warning: Removed 6 rows containing missing values (`geom_line()`).

The default is to drop one level (the first), but this can be changed or bypassed by setting the `dropLevels argument.

plot(factExam, dropLevels = 2)
## Warning in plot(plotData, ...): NAs introduced by coercion
## Warning: Removed 14 rows containing missing values (`geom_line()`).

plot(factExam, dropLevels = NULL)
## Warning in plot(plotData, ...): NAs introduced by coercion
## Warning: Removed 20 rows containing missing values (`geom_line()`).

Summarizing a MarkedPointProcess object gives additional informations on the number of points for each unit and each mark.

summary(pointExam)
## Class: MarkedPointProcess 
## Dimensions: 4046 x 5 
## Index variable: time 
## 
## 4 units.
##    id: A B C D
## 
## 5 variables.
##    gender foo bar ALPHA BETA
## 
##   grid-points time-range gender median(foo) median(bar) #ALPHA #BETA
## A        1013     [0;10]      M  -7.3237089    46.62783      6     6
## B        1015     [0;10]      M   0.9347193    37.45946      8     6
## C        1007     [0;10]      M  18.1055244    14.32739      2     4
## D        1011     [0;10]      F   5.0997277    57.70206      3     7

A combined plot for unit A.

plot(subset(pointExam, id =="A"))

Plotting the point process data only.

plot(pointExam[, -(1:3)])

Or a slightly different version.

plot(pointExam[, -(1:3)], y = "id") + facet_null()

Plotting the continuous process data only.

plot(pointExam[, -c(4,5)])

or

plot(as(pointExam, "ContinuousProcess"))

Some modifications of the plot.

plot(pointExam, allUnitData = TRUE) + facet_grid(.~gender)

plot(pointExam, y = "id", allUnitData = TRUE) + facet_grid(variable~gender, scale = "free_y")

plot(pointExam, y = "foo") 

plot(pointExam, y = "@top", allUnitData = TRUE) + facet_grid(.~gender)

plot(pointExam, y = "@bottom", allUnitData = TRUE) + facet_grid(gender~., scales = "free_y")

plot(pointExam, y = "id") + facet_null()

A JumpProcess data set has points with the same marks as the variable names in the ContinuousProcess part of the data set. In addition, to each point there is a size of the jump associated.

jumpExam
## Class: JumpProcess 
## Dimensions: 4041 x 6 
## Index variable: time 
## 
## 4 units.
##    id: A B C D
## 
## 6 variables.
##    gender foo bar bar foo jump
plot(jumpExam)

We can again use ggplot2 for modifications

plot(jumpExam) + facet_grid(variable ~ .) + aes(color = id)

Removing objects.

rm(contExam)
rm(pointExam)
rm(jumpExam)
